-------What is Diameter?

👉 Diameter = Longest path between any two nodes in the tree.
It is measured by the number of edges.

Example
      1
     / \
    2   3
   / \
  4   5
Longest path:
4 → 2 → 1 → 3
Edges:
4-2 = 1
2-1 = 1
1-3 = 1

Total = 3
Diameter = 3

Diameter through that node =
Height of Left Subtree
+
Height of Right Subtree

Trick to Remember ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐

For every node ask:

"If this node is the center, what is the longest path passing through it?"

Answer:

Left Height + Right Height


class Solution {
public:
    int diameter = 0;

    int height(TreeNode* root) {

        if (root == NULL)
            return 0;

        int left = height(root->left);
        int right = height(root->right);

        diameter = max(diameter, left + right);

        return 1 + max(left, right);
    }

    int diameterOfBinaryTree(TreeNode* root) {

        height(root);

        return diameter;
    }
};

Diameter of Binary Tree – Interview Explanation (5 Simple Points)
***The diameter is the longest path between any two nodes in the tree.
***I use DFS (Depth First Search) to visit every node once.
***At each node, I calculate the height of the left subtree and the height of the right subtree.
The diameter through that node is left height + right height. I keep updating the maximum diameter.
I return the height as 1 + max(left, right). This solves the problem in one traversal with O(n) time complexity.
Easy Memory Trick
Height    = 1 + max(left, right)

Diameter  = left + right

Answer    = Maximum Diameter

Take the maximum for all nodes.
